entry.title: update shadow rounded corners when exit overview
entry.content:
When RoundedWindows is enabled, the window shadow should also have

rounded corners. However, when exiting overview mode, the shadow

of the window no longer has rounded corners. It is because the window

frame rounded corner radius updates on

chromeos::kIsShowingInOverviewKey changes but the shadow does not.



To solve the issue, we should also update the shadow rounded corners

when property chromeos::kIsShowingInOverviewKey changes. This is a

platform dependent behavior so we added an interface

ShouldUpdateShadowOnWindowPropertyChange in

wm::ShadowControllerDelegate and implemented it in

ash::WmShadowControllerDelegate.



UpdateShadowRoundedCornersEnterExitOverview



Test: WmShadowControllerDelegateTest.\

entry.title: [3PCD][Mode B] Create base feature flag for Mode B Experiment
entry.content:
The 3PCD Mode B Experiment (https://developer.chrome.com/blog/shipping-privacy-sandbox/#testing)

will use this feature flag to place clients into the different

experiment arms: Mode B, Mode B', Control and Control'. This experiment

will compare experiences for users who have 3P Cookies disabled and Ads

APIs enabled (Mode B) against users with both 3P Cookies and Ads APIs

enabled (Control) and compare users who have both 3P Cookies and the new

privacy sandbox APIs disabled (Mode B') with an equal-sized group of

users who have both 3P Cookies and Ads APIs enabled (Control').



This experiment will use FeatureParams to mix and match functionality

variables: whether 3P cookies are disabled, whether Ads APIs are

disabled, and whether traffic should be labeled.



Also, create necessary directory files for Mode B Experiment work.

entry.title: [ios][af] Keyboard, Only take the suggestions from latest query
entry.content:
The keyboard doesn't seem to have logic in place to handle concurrent

autofill suggestions requests (which are async in nature).



It is not impossible that a query done at `t` overrides the results of

a more recent query done a `t + 1` if the first query completes after

the second query, as it is not possible to know which query will

complete first. (could be the case in reality but can't be trusted).



We assume that the most recent query is the one that is the best fit

for the current context where the keyboard is used.



This patch also avoids updating the suggestions view model

unnecessarily with suggestions data that is already known to be

replaced soon.



--



An alternative approach could be to only allow overriding suggestions

if the query timestamp is bigger than the timestamp of the

current suggestions.



This would better guarantee that there are at least some suggestions

displayed, but can't guarantee the relevance.

entry.title: [ozone] Commit the surface tree after SetShape() called
entry.content:
Currently SetShape() sets double buffered state on the shell surface

corresponding to the toplevel window server side [1]. This state is

applied to the hosting widget only after a commit is received from

the client for the root surface.



In some circumstances this can lead to the shape not taking effect

immediately (see crbug.com/1158733#c29). This CL ensures that clients

propagate a commit after SetShape() has been called for the top level

window, making sure that the change occurs server-side shortly after.

entry.title: Correctly determine if a proxy is for IP protection.
entry.content:
The previous solution relied on the assumption that a ProxyServer

instance returned from `ProxyDelegate::OnResolveProxy()` would arrive

intact at `ProxyDelegate::OnBeforeTunnelRequest()`. This is not the

case.



Instead, `OnBeforeTunnelRequest()` searches the IP protection proxy list

for the proxy hostname. This is a little slower, but proxy connections

are pooled and reused so should not have a substantial impact on speed.



This also introduces a race between changes to the IP protection proxy

list and connections to a proxy. If a proxy is removed from the list,

and `OnBeforeTunnelRequest()` is called for that proxy, then an auth

token will not be added, the connection will fail, and the browser will

fall back to the next proxy. Since the proxy was removed from the proxy

list, failing and falling back is actually the appropriate behavior.



This reverts the addition of `ProxyServer::is_for_ip_protection()` in

crrev.com/c/4818009, as that field is not preserved and no longer

needed.

entry.title: [view-transition] Stop BrowserCompositorMac from calling WasShown while
entry.content:
hidden



Calling DelegatedFrameHost::WasShown() while hidden will assign

`first_local_surface_id_after_navigation_` with the LocalSurfaceId

of `BrowserCompositorMac`. This LocalSurfaceId is considered

stale for BFCache restoration with ViewTransition because such

restoration will have customized primary and fallback SurfaceIds.



When the fallback content timer is up, the stale value of

`first_local_surface_id_after_navigation_` will be used to reset the

fallback SurfaceId, which confuses Viz, causing a white screen.



What this CL means:

- As long as we are hidden: HasNoCompositor.

- `SetParentUiLayer` used to be always "successful" because even though

we are hidden, we use UseParentLayerCompositor to represent the state.

With this CL, `SetParentUiLayer` won't re-parent `root_layer_` if we

are hidden. `root_layer_` will be re-parented next time we become

visible (HasNoCompositor->UseParentLayerCompositor).

entry.title: Make ChromeDeviceAuthenticatorFactory per profile
entry.content:
This CL is part of a bigger refactoring process of the DeviceAuthenticator class.



The purpose of this CL is to make the ChromeDeviceAuthenticatorFactory

per profile (by creating a proxy which is a profile keyed service). This

change requires to also record the last successful authentication

timestamp per profile (and not have it common for the entire browser

instance, as it was before).



Before, timestamp of last successful authentication was held by

ChromeDeviceAuthenticatorCommon (which extends DeviceAuthenticator) and

was available per browser instance. This timestamp was moved in the

logic of ChromeDeviceAuthenticatorFactory (more specifically, in the

proxy), and it is available per profile.



Before, there was only one ChromeDeviceAuthenticatorCommon instance,

shared using a scoped_ref pointer.

We don't need this anymore, so, in a different CL, we will make it that

every time someone requires a new device authenticator, it will be

created as an unique_ptr and will be connected to the current profile

via the proxy created by the ChromeDeviceAuthenticatorFactory.



Design doc for refactoring: http://docs/document/d/15E8t2BcmN241P-1xpLzYXwROrTzzb1-fS9LnXRnHRKc?resourcekey=0-MgxW9Z7T5rY5AzhcyTg__w#heading=h.xgjl2srtytjt .

entry.title: [PA] Change |FreeNoHooks| to |Free<kNoHooks>|
entry.content:
This is a refactoring change to PA. This change should affect only

inline-ness of |FreeNoHooks| calls in tests.



- Rename |FreeNoHooks| to |FreeInline|

- Rename |FreeNoHooksInUnknownRoot| to |FreeInlineInUnknownRoot|

- Add |FreeFlags::kNoHooks|

- Allow using |kNoHooks| in |Free***|

- There should be no overhead because all conditional branching is

performed at compile-time.

- Rewrite all |FreeNoHooks| usage to:

- |Free| if in tests

- |FreeInline| otherwise

- Rewrite all |FreeNoHooksInUnknownRoot| usage to:

- |FreeInUnknownRoot| if in tests

- |FreeInlineInUnknownRoot| otherwise



Context:

Historically |FreeNoHooks| existed to make hook-less allocation

faster by omitting some conditional branching based on allocation

flags. However, https://crrev.com/c/4722182 constexpr-nized flags

so there is no performance overhead.

Making it private makes allocation flow and PA's API more simple.
